article.headline: Heat's playoff chances sinking fast

images.caption: The Celtics make life hard for Eddie Jones on this drive Monday.

article.linkText: Strickland's season-high leads Celtics past Heat
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- The Boston Celtics knew just where to look in the absence of Kenny Anderson. Erick Strickland was more than ready to come in and handle the point. Strickland scored a season-high 23 points, including a pair of 3-pointers late in the fourth quarter, leading Boston to a 87-82 victory over Miami on Monday night. Strickland helped the Celtics pull away in the fourth quarter and secure a much-needed win. "I just wanted to be ready and get my rhythm as quickly as possible," Strickland said. "I'm trying to stay consistent and get the extra shots." Boston, which had lost three of its previous four after winning seven straight, moved 1 1/2 games ahead of Milwaukee for the No. 3 spot in the Eastern Conference. Miami lost for the third straight time and has dropped five of its last seven. The Heat, once a half-game out of the playoffs, fell four games behind Indiana for the final playoff spot. The Heat's loss also clinched a playoff spot for New Jersey, which was idle. "I don't care about the standings," Miami center Alonzo Mourning said. "My main concern is for us to start winning. If we start winning, the standings will take care of itself." Anderson sat out with a sprained ankle sustained against Detroit on Friday and will miss another four games while on the injured list. Tony Delk started in place of Anderson, but it was Strickland who stepped in to fill the gap, scoring 10 points in the final 2 1/2 minutes. Strickland's 3-pointer opened a 79-73 lead with 2:07 left, and he hit a drive inside the lane for an 81-78 lead with 1:01 left. After Jim Jackson pulled Miami within one point, Strickland again dropped in a 3-pointer with 24 seconds remaining. "That was a really big shot late in the game, a big swing," Strickland said. "We have a deep team, and you have to be ready. Kenny's injury was unexpected, so I had to come out and play with as much energy as I could. Kenny is a big part of what we do, especially with his leadership." Eddie House missed a 3-pointer for the Heat, and Strickland hit a pair of free throws with 16 seconds to go. Paul Pierce scored 19 points and Antoine Walker 17 for Boston. Alonzo Mourning scored 20 points to go along with 10 rebounds, and Eddie Jones had 19 points for Miami. The Celtics reached 40 wins for the first time since the 1992-93 season and now turn their focus on securing home-court advantage in the first-round of the playoffs. "It was a wonderful win for our team," Boston coach Jim O'Brien said. "It was a very competitive game, and both teams wouldn't give the other an inch. The difference was that we didn't turn it over and they did." The Heat committed 21 turnovers and shot 38 percent for the game. "We are not making timely shots," Miami coach Pat Riley said. "They absolutely swarmed Zo tonight. He had 17 free throws, but we couldn't get the ball inside. They gave us the perimeter and played soft there. We drove it to the basket, but we needed to make another half-dozen jumpers tonight." Game notes
Riley made good on his promise to shake up his team, inserting Jackson at small forward over Kendall Gill. ...The road team has won the last five games in the series. ...The Celtics are 9-8 since the Feb. 20 trade that brought them Delk and Rodney Rogers from Phoenix in exchange for Randy Brown, Joe Johnson, Milt Palacio and a conditional 2002 first-round pick. ...The Celtics shot just 21.7 percent in the first quarter, making 5 of 23 attempts. ... Boston is 19-18 on the road.
